                  characteristics. The interaction of natural and sexual
                  selection is also pivotal in a model where sexual selection
                  facilitates ecological speciation even in the absence of
                  diverging female preferences. In view of these results, it is
                  counterproductive to consider ecological and sexual selection
                  models as contrasting and incompatible views on speciation,
                  one being dominant over the other. Instead, an integrative
                  perspective is needed to achieve a thorough and coherent
                  understanding of adaptive speciation.},
